### useParams

`useParams` returns an object of key-value pairs for dynamic route parameters. It lets you extract variables from the URL path.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

const params = useParams();
```

### Route Definition

```jsx
<Route path="/users/:userId" element={<UserProfile />} />
<Route path="/products/:category/:id" element={<ProductPage />} />
```

### Accessing Params

```jsx
function UserProfile() {
  const { userId } = useParams();
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(setUser);
  }, [userId]);

  return user ? <h1>{user.name}</h1> : <p>Loading...</p>;
}
```

### Multiple Params

```jsx
function ProductPage() {
  const { category, id } = useParams();
  return (
    <div>
      <p>Category: {category}</p>
      <p>Product ID: {id}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

| URL | Route Pattern | useParams Returns |
|-----|--------------|-------------------|
| `/users/42` | `/users/:userId` | `{ userId: '42' }` |
| `/posts/5/comments/3` | `/posts/:postId/comments/:commentId` | `{ postId: '5', commentId: '3' }` |
| `/products/electronics/123` | `/products/:category/:id` | `{ category: 'electronics', id: '123' }` |

> **Key Point:** URL parameters are always strings. Parse them to numbers if needed. useParams triggers a re-render when the params change, making it safe to use in dependency arrays.

codeExample:
import { useParams, Link } from 'react-router-dom';

function BlogPost() {
  const { slug } = useParams();

  return (
    <div>
      <Link to="/blog">Back to Blog</Link>
      <h1>Post: {slug}</h1>
    </div>
  );
}

// Route: <Route path="/blog/:slug" element={<BlogPost />} />
